Objective 1.1 — Why Spring Exists: IoC, DI, and the Container
Why Spring exists
Before Spring, Java enterprise apps (J2EE) required you to manually wire together every dependency. If OrderService needed a PaymentGateway, you'd write new PaymentGateway() inside OrderService. That creates tight coupling — OrderService now controls the creation and lifecycle of its own dependencies, which makes it nearly impossible to swap implementations or test in isolation.

Spring's core answer to this is Inversion of Control (IoC): instead of your code creating its dependencies, you hand that responsibility to a framework — the IoC container. Your class just declares what it needs, and the container figures out how to provide it.

The practical payoffs are:

Decoupling — OrderService depends on an interface, not a concrete class. Swap the implementation without touching OrderService.
Testability — inject a mock PaymentGateway in tests instead of the real one.
Enterprise integration — transactions, security, caching, etc. can be layered on without polluting business logic.
IoC vs Dependency Injection vs Dependency Lookup
IoC is the principle. There are two ways to implement it:

Dependency Injection (DI) — the container pushes dependencies into your class. Your class is passive; it just receives what it needs. This is what Spring uses.

Dependency Lookup — your class actively asks the container for a dependency (e.g. context.getBean(...)). Your class is aware of the container. This breaks testability and is considered an anti-pattern for application code.

⚠️ EXAM TRAP: Calling ApplicationContext.getBean() inside your business logic is dependency lookup, not injection — and it's the thing Spring is trying to help you avoid. The exam may ask you to distinguish these.

BeanFactory vs ApplicationContext
Both are IoC containers. ApplicationContext extends BeanFactory and adds production-grade features.

Feature	BeanFactory	ApplicationContext
Basic DI	✅	✅
Eager singleton init	❌ (lazy by default)	✅ (at startup)
Event publishing	❌	✅
MessageSource (i18n)	❌	✅
BeanPostProcessor auto-registration	Manual	✅ Automatic
AOP integration	Limited	✅
In practice: always use ApplicationContext. BeanFactory exists mostly for constrained environments (embedded devices, etc.) where memory is critical. The exam may ask which one supports events or i18n — the answer is always ApplicationContext.

The three DI types
1. Constructor injection — PREFERRED

@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final PaymentGateway paymentGateway;

    public OrderService(PaymentGateway paymentGateway) {  // Spring injects here
        this.paymentGateway = paymentGateway;
    }
}
2. Setter injection — use when dependency is optional
@Service
public class OrderService {
    private PaymentGateway paymentGateway;

    @Autowired
    public void setPaymentGateway(PaymentGateway paymentGateway) {
        this.paymentGateway = paymentGateway;
    }
}
3. Field injection — convenient but problematic
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private PaymentGateway paymentGateway;  // Can't make final, hard to Inversion of Control
}
Why constructor injection is preferred:

The field can be final — guarantees the dependency is never null after construction.
Dependencies are explicit in the constructor signature — easy to see what a class needs.
Works with plain new in unit tests — no Spring context required.
With a single constructor in Spring 4.3+, @Autowired is optional — Spring infers it.
Field injection hides dependencies and makes the class untestable without a Spring context or a reflection-based injector.

